Nicholas 20-Sep-20 09:17 PM
Wait what's up?
So essentially you have a separate project for each functional component so they're completely in isolated from each other and deployed/built independently
i.e. Booking is one project, Auth would be another, Account would also be a different one which included all account related functionality such as update information such as security and creating an account
Anything with Booking should be its own solution
So from what I understand @Giorady has two projects since he's working on two components/microservices and @Thanh you have one since it's one area
Does that make sense?
It's not isolated based on functionality per say but it's isolated by business areas/domain (edited)
The login process is separate from anything account related and so is the booking separated from all of that (edited)
If booking had 10 functions i.e. create, list, update, compare x to y, etc it's still one project
@Thanh ^
Here's a decent guide: https://medium.com/platform-engineer/microservices-design-guide-eca0b799a7e8
Microservices Design Guide
Everyone has heard about Microservices. But do you know how to design one?
Just reading the first part for "concepts" should be enough to explain their isolation
Giorady 20-Sep-20 09:27 PM
sorry i might misinformed you, yeah it should be per domain not per function

package sept.rmit.booking.web; import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired; import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*; import sept.rmit.booking.model.Booking; import sept.rmit.booking.service.BookingService; @RestController @RequestMapping("/api/booking") @CrossOrigin(origins = "localhost:8080") public class BookingController { @Autowired private BookingService bookingService; @GetMapping("get-all") public Iterable<Booking> getAll(){ return bookingService.getBookings(); } @PostMapping("add") public @ResponseBody String addBooking(@RequestBody Booking booking){ boolean isExist = bookingService.isExist(booking.getCustomerId(), booking.getWorkingDateId()); if(isExist == false){ bookingService.create(booking.getCustomerId(), booking.getBookingDate(), booking.getWorkingDateId(), booking.getServiceId(), booking.getBookingStatusId()); return "New Booking Added"; }else{ return "Duplicate Entry"; } } }
@Giorady so the origins part is just where you put where the front end is hosted

Nicholas 05-Oct-20 03:06 PM
@Gihan Here's the constraints for all the tickets you requested.
Attachment: message.txt (4.63 KB)
SEPT-93 Constraints - Creates the base DNS resource in AWS. - Serves as a point of dependency for other core resources requiring DNS. - Should output the zone id where the DNS record was created. - Should output the root domain name (FQDN) which was setup for the environment. - Validation to ensure the AWS region provided is valid. - The region is automatically injected by the root configuration for Terragrunt for a particular environment.
SEPT-95 Constraints - Setup the EKS resources for managed Kubernetes in AWS. - Wire the cluster up to the previously provisioned core orchestration network dependency. - Allocates IAM users access to the cluster. - Configured autoscaling for the worker nodes using autoscaling groups (ASGs) with minimum, maximum and desired (average) capacities. - Custom instance type(s) can be provided for cost optimisation. - Targets spot instances for cost optimisation. - Provisions a public IP address against the cluster for external access outside of the private network (VPC) - Configuration is also setup for the development environment.
SEPT-96 Constraints - A modular workspace for provisioning Kubernetes namespaces. - Automatically connects to the appropriate Kubernetes cluster through the initialised provider. - Multiple namespaces can be provisioned at will. - By default it won't provision any additional namespaces. - The orchestration workspace provides the two additional namespaces we want provisioned; one for applications and another for their ingress services.
SEPT-97 Constraints - A modular workspace for applying individual role-based access control (RBAC) to IAM members and groups within AWS. - The names of groups and members is completely customised when the module is called and must be provided as there's no defaults. - Custom access rules can also be provided when calling the module. - There is a default set of permissions assigned automatically if none are specified. - The RBAC module is called directly from the core cluster module.
SEPT-98 Constraints - Uses separate workspace(s) for abstraction from the core EKS workspace. - Manages the spot instances provisioned as cluster workers. - Utilises the AWS built helm chart for handling spot instance termination. - Provisioned with the latest constraints such as repo and version. - Is in a separate namespace from the applications. - All chart constraints are customisable to upgrade versions or fallback to older versions if necessary. - All the chart constraints are automatically filled by default with the latest values. - Sets up an autoscaling policy for average CPU utilisation against the autoscaling group (ASG). - Is part of a cluster add-on isolation (optional optimisations to the EKS cluster) which is provisioned by the main orchestration.
SEPT-99 Constraints - Separate workspace(s) for ingress to further abstract the implementation. - Setup ingress for traffic destined to the EKS (Kubernetes) cluster from an external network. - Provisions a wildcard certificate against the EKS (root) domain name (FQDN) to support subdomain allocation per application. - Utilises nginx for controlling ingress within the EKS (Kubernetes) cluster. - Deploys nginx using helm based on the latest constraints for chart repo and versions. - Isolates the services into a separate namespace from the applications. - Custom annotations are pre-applied for handling the SSL certificate. - Additional annotations can be applies through the workspace variable(s). - All chart constraints are customisable to upgrade versions or fallback to older versions if necessary. - The nginx module is controlled by the routing workspace which adds additional ingress annotations for traffic control. - The hostname provisioned against nginx is available as a dependency for other modules.
SEPT-100 Constraints - A separate workspace for handling routing to abstract the implementation. - Provisions the route 53 records for validating the EKS domain certificate(s). - Creates an A record for connecting the DNS record to the EKS instances public IP address. - Outputs the domain name provisioned as a dependency for other modules/workspaces. - Configures dependencies with core DNS to automatically retrieve the environments root domain (FQDN). - Validation is made against the provided domain name to ensure it's a valid FQDN. - Update the root configuration to automatically populate environment details for regions and resources.
SEPT-101 Constraints - Removes the LFS dependency against the build pipelines. - Steer away from the RMIT restrictions against LFS bandwidth. - Address recent build pipeline failures caused by external parties. - Removes all binaries from the build pipelines.
Yeah, kinda wouldn't fit into a single message (edited)

actually another question about git
its claiming some of my files are untracked but these are files ive already pushed from a different branch do you know how to fix it?
like ill be in the development branch but its showing stuff from my booking branch
Nicholas 06-Oct-20 11:37 PM
Typically you want to remove all .gitignore files that aren't in the root since they scope based on what's most relative to the files
^ can also cause that when switch branches without pulling the latest changes
since your local scope now has more files ignored than before
then when you switch you lose that new .gitignore so it thinks there's still files to commit
Thanh 06-Oct-20 11:42 PM
that makes a lot of sense

Nicholas 15-Oct-20 05:18 PM
Typically tests would run against the dev database (which is what this currently is) and all other environments would be completely separate from this process and unaffected
I wouldn't create a standalone database for tests as QA would run regressions and automation tests against this main database anyway (since it's what the app connects to) and you'll be bringing in too much additional complexity
So either I would make the data unique for each push or cleanup only what you've created; the first option is more ideal but for this case either works (edited)

Nicholas 16-Oct-20 09:49 AM
@Gihan I'm guessing that's a dev question right
@Giorady No. Your axios endpoint is what's defined in the api and your baseURL is what is against the nginx proxy within k8s
Either the route needs to be identical to what the nginx server classifies as the ingress for the application and it won't strip the path using rewrite target
If it isn't then it needs to rewrite the URL by excluding the ingress route prior to delegating the request onto the application
That explains it. If it's too complicated change your API routes to include the prefixes I recommended previously (edited)
@Giorady Yes, either make it - Registration: /api/registration/register or /register Profile: /api/profile/me or /me Authentication/Login: /api/authentication/login or /login
The first options. Then you'll be in-sync with the k8s nginx proxy and won't be confused on the different URLs
Otherwise, if you don't want to change it apply my recommendations in the PR
I can't provide much more information than that
